\section{Current-induced motion of magnetic skyrmions at zero temperature}

We start with a numerical investigation of the current-velocity relation of magnetic skyrmions in $N$-layer racetracks, with $N=1,2,3,4$, at zero temperature: See Figure~\ref{FIG2}.

Let us recapitulate the current-induced motion of a magnetic skyrmion in a FM monolayer racetrack, which undergoes a transverse motion toward the upper edge of the racetrack because of the skyrmion Hall effect \textcolor{blue}{(see Supplementary Movie 1)}. We show the trajectory at a moderate driving current of $j=10$ MA cm$^{-2}$ in Figure~\ref{FIG2}(a). The moving skyrmion reaches a stable velocity of $v_x\sim 70$ m s$^{-1}$ and has a transverse shift of $\sim 5$ nm due to the skyrmion Hall effect. It does not touch the edge because of the repulsive force from the edge.

Nevertheless, when $j>10$ MA cm$^{-2}$, it is destroyed by touching the edge shortly after the driving current is applied \textcolor{blue}{(see Supplementary Movie 1)}.

Let us also recapitulate the current-induced motion of a bilayer skyrmion in a bilayer racetrack \textcolor{blue}{(see Supplementary Movie 2)}. It goes straight in the bilayer SAF racetrack as a result of the suppression of the skyrmion Hall effect ($Q_{\text{tot}}=0$). The trajectory at a moderate driving current of $j=20$ MA cm$^{-2}$ is shown in Figure~\ref{FIG2}(b), where it reaches a stable speed of $\sim 70$ m s$^{-1}$. The bilayer skyrmion strictly moves along the central line ($y=25$ nm) of the racetrack.

We go on to study the current-induced motion of a trilayer skyrmion with $Q_{\text{tot}}=1$ (see Figure~\ref{FIG2}(c)), and a quadrilayer skyrmion with $Q_{\text{tot}}=0$ (see Figure~\ref{FIG2}(d)). The trilayer skyrmion experiences the skyrmion Hall effect \textcolor{blue}{(see Supplementary Movie 3)} as in the case of the monolayer skyrmion. On the other hand, the quadrilayer skyrmion moves reliably in the quadrilayer SAF racetrack even at a strong driving current \textcolor{blue}{(see Supplementary Movie 4)}, demonstrating the suppression of the skyrmion Hall effect as in the case of a bilayer skyrmion. The quadrilayer skyrmion moves along the central line ($y=25$ nm) of the racetrack.

We compare the skyrmion Hall effects at $N=1$ and $N=3$ quantitatively. We show the skyrmion Hall angle $v_{y}/v_{x}$ as a function of time $t$ in Figure~\ref{FIG3}(a) for $N=1,3$. The skyrmion angle is anti-proportional to $N$. Namely, the skyrmion Hall effect for $N=3$ is three times smaller than that for $N=1$. The theoretical expectation equation~(\ref{HallAngle}) explains the numerical data remarkably well with the choice of $\alpha\mathcal{D}=0.57$.

In Figure~\ref{FIG3}(b), we show the velocity $v_{x}$ as a function of the applied driving current density $j$ for the motion of $N$-layer skyrmions, $N=1,2,3,4$. We have fitted the data successfully by theoretical expectation equation~(\ref{Velocity}) with the use of $\alpha\mathcal{D}=0.57$. The velocity $v_{x}$ is almost anti-proportional to $N$ as shown in Figure~\ref{FIG3}(c). This is because the driving current is only applied to the bottom FM layer L1.

A comment is in order on the further improvement of the $j-v$ relation of the magnetic skyrmions in the racetracks. Here, taking the bilayer skyrmion as an example, we also investigate the $j-v$ curve when the driving current is applied in both constituent FM layers of the bilayer racetrack, which is plotted in Figure~\ref{FIG3}(b) as a dashed curve. It can be seen that, when both FM layers are driven by the current, the $j-v$ relation of the bilayer skyrmion matches well with that of a monolayer skyrmion moving in a FM monolayer racetrack in the small driving current regime. When $j=10$ MA cm$^{-2}$, the velocity of the monolayer skyrmion is $v_x=70$ m s$^{-1}$, while the velocity of the bilayer skyrmion is $v_x=72$ m s$^{-1}$.

\section{Current-induced motion of magnetic skyrmions at finite temperatures}

We proceed to investigate the effects of random thermal perturbations on the motion of $N$-layer skyrmions.

Figure~\ref{FIG4} demonstrates the motion of a monolayer (bilayer) skyrmion driven by a moderate current of $j=10$ ($20$) MA cm$^{-2}$ at temperatures ranging from ${\text{T}}=0$ K to ${\text{T}}=300$ K \textcolor{blue}{(see Supplementary Movies 5 and 6)}.

A monolayer skyrmion moves safely from the left to the right terminal of the racetrack at ${\text{T}}=0$ and $50$ K. However, when the temperature ${\text{T}}$ is increased and larger than $100$ K, it becomes unstable and is destroyed by touching the upper edge. Figures~\ref{FIG5}(a)-(g) show its trajectories at ${\text{T}}=0$, $50$, $100$, $150$, $200$, $250$, and $300$ K, respectively. At ${\text{T}}=0$, as we have already stated, the transverse shift is constant due to the balance between the skyrmion Hall effect and the edge effect. At a finite temperature, the motion is affected by thermal effects, where the transverse shift is fluctuating. It is destroyed when the fluctuated skyrmion touches the edge. Indeed, it is destroyed after having moved $\sim 200$ nm at ${\text{T}}=100$ K. When ${\text{T}}$ is raised to room temperature, that is, ${\text{T}}=300$ K, the monolayer skyrmion is destroyed very shortly after the driving current is applied.

On the other hand, a bilayer skyrmion moves safely from the left to the right terminal of the racetrack even at ${\text{T}}=300$ K. The corresponding trajectories of a bilayer skyrmion at ${\text{T}}=0$, $50$, $100$, $150$, $200$, $250$, and $300$ K, are given in Figures~\ref{FIG5}(h)-(n), respectively. Since the bilayer skyrmion exhibits no transverse shift caused by the skyrmion Hall effect, it is not destroyed by touching the edge as the racetrack width is wide enough.

In Figures~\ref{FIG6}(a)-(d), we show the distributions of the $y$-position of a $N$-layer skyrmion for $\sim 300$ nm of motion at different temperatures ${\text{T}}$, which are fitted by using the Gaussian distribution.

In Figures~\ref{FIG6}(e)-(f), we show the mean value $y_{0}$ and standard deviation $\sigma_{y}$ of the distribution of the $y$-position as functions of ${\text{T}}$ corresponding to Figure~\ref{FIG6}(a)-(d).

The mean $y_{0}$ is around the one half of the sample width for $N=2$ and $N=4$ since a skyrmion goes straight reflecting the absence of the skyrmion Hall effect. 

On the other hand, the mean $y_{0}$ is away from the one half of the sample width for $N=1$ and $N=3$ due to the skyrmion Hall effect.

The deviation is larger for $N=1$ than $N=3$, which indicates that the skyrmion Hall effect is larger in $N=1$ than $N=3$.

In Figure~\ref{FIG5} we see that a monolayer skyrmion can go further at ${\text{T}}=150$ K than at ${\text{T}}=100$ K. This occurs accidentally due to a choice of the thermal random seed. In order to evaluate and examine the effect of the thermal random seed on the simulation results, we perform each simulation at a given finite temperature $10$ times individually with different thermal random seed values. The trajectories of a monolayer skyrmion at ${\text{T}}=50$ and $100$ K with three selected random seed values are shown in Figures~\ref{FIG7}(a)-(b), respectively, where a moderate driving current of $j=10$ MA cm$^{-2}$ is applied. It can be seen that the trajectories at a certain finite temperature with different random seed values are modestly influenced by thermal perturbations. At ${\text{T}}=50$ K, although the motion of the monolayer skyrmion is fluctuating, it reaches the right terminal of the racetrack in all $10$ simulations with different random seed values. At ${\text{T}}=100$ K, it is destroyed by touching the upper edge of the racetrack in all $10$ simulations with different random seed values.

On the other hand, the bilayer skyrmion is safely conveyed between the two terminals without touching the edge in all these simulations even at ${\text{T}}=300$ K, as shown in Figures~\ref{FIG7}(c).

\section{Conclusion}

We have studied the motion of magnetic skyrmions in multilayer SAF racetracks in contrast to the motion of skyrmions in conventional FM monolayer racetracks.

The thermal effects on their motions have been investigated by including random thermal perturbations in the simulations.

We have found that a moving bilayer skyrmion is much more stable than a moving monolayer skyrmion, even when the temperature effect is taken into account.

The detrimental effect of the skyrmion Hall effect on the moving monolayer skyrmion is enhanced as temperature increases, while the bilayer skyrmion is immune from the skyrmion Hall effect.

The bilayer skyrmion is intrinsically more stable than the monolayer skyrmion since the two skyrmions consisting the bilayer skyrmion are tightly bounded by the interlayer AFM exchange coupling.

Namely, the thermal fluctuation acts independently on the top and the bottom layers of the bilayer, which is almost canceled when the two skyrmions are tightly bounded.

The odd-even effect of the constituent FM layer number on the skyrmion Hall effect in SAF layers has also been demonstrated.

Due to the suppression of the skyrmion Hall effect, the magnetic skyrmions have no transverse motion in SAF racetracks with even constituent FM layers.

In conclusion, the bilayer SAF racetrack is a preferred host for skyrmion transmission since it realizes a minimum system which does not show the skyrmion Hall effect.

